 1380","1381":"1381","South Ferriby, North Lincolnshire, England":"South Ferriby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Swansea, Wales, United Kingdom":"Swansea, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Maud De Cantilupe was born about 1349. She married Sheriff Thomas de Kydale of Lincolnshire, Knight about 1380, in South Ferriby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"ABT 1349–":"umbes 1349–Surnud","1345–1375":"1345–1375","1343–1381":"1343–1381","1365–Male":"1365–Surnud","1349–Female":"1349–Surnud","1349":"1349","1345":"1345","1365":"1365","1343":"1343","1375":"1375","about 1365":"umbes 1365","ABT 1349":"umbes 1349","Abt 1380":"umbes 1380","1381":"1381","South Ferriby, North Lincolnshire, England":"South Ferriby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Swansea, Wales, United Kingdom":"Swansea, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1349–":"noin 1349–Kuollut","1345–1375":"1345–1375","1343–1381":"1343–1381","1365–Male":"1365–Kuollut","1349–Female":"1349–Kuollut","1349":"1349","1345":"1345","1365":"1365","1343":"1343","1375":"1375","about 1365":"noin 1365","ABT 1349":"noin 1349","Abt 1380":"noin 1380","1381":"1381","South Ferriby, North Lincolnshire, England":"South Ferriby, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Swansea, Wales, United Kingdom":"Swansea, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"ABT 1349–":"environ 1349–Décédée","1345–1375":"1345–1375","1343–1381":"1343–1381","1365–Male":"1365–Décédé","1349–Female":"1349–Décédée","1349":"1349","1345":"1345","1365":"1365","1343":"1343","1375":"1375","about 1365":"environ 1365","ABT 1349":"environ 1349","Abt 1380":"environ 1380","1381":"1381","South Ferriby, North Lincolnshire, England":"South Ferriby, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Swansea, Wales, United Kingdom":"Swansea, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Maud De Cantilupe est née environ 1349. Elle a épousé Sheriff Thomas de Kydale of Lincolnshire, Knight environ 1380, à South Ferriby, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni."},"de":{"ABT 1349–":"um 1349–Verstorben","1345–1375":"1345–1375","1343–1381":"1343–1381","1365–Male":"1365–Verstorben","1349–Female":"1349–Verstorb